The paper is structured as follows: Section 2 reviews the theoretical foundations: information asymmetries in digital markets, the role of electronic word-of-mouth in consumer decision-making, and how firms strategically manage online reputation. It then examines institutional preconditions that shape platform content governance, establishing a research framework for comparing removal patterns across jurisdictions. Section 3 describes the research design and data sources, detailing sample collection from the Digital Services Act transparency database and the Lumen Database, followed by descriptive statistics of removal requests and outcomes across EU member states. Section 4 presents results, interpreting observed patterns of review deletion and identifying removal patterns in Germany. Section 5 discusses managerial implications for both firms and platforms, acknowledges limitations of the current analysis, and identifies directions for future research on suppressive reputation management as an emerging competitive practice.